<font face="Arial" size="+2"><center><p><b>Motion of the Planets: Comparative Sizes</b></p></center>
</font><font face="Arial" size="--">

<p>Size of planets:</p>
<ul>
<li>The Sun is the largest object in the Solar System, the rest of the bodies are dwarfed by it.
<center><img src="23103bskepl101.png">
<!--img src="23103bsPlanetsSizeCompare1.png"--></center>
</li>
<li>The diameter of the Sun is 100 times that of Earth, so, for comparison
<center><table>
<tr><td>Sun </td><td>= size of basketball </td><td></td></tr>
<tr><td>Earth </td><td>= size of pin </td><td></td></tr>
<tr><td>Jupiter </td><td>= ping-pong ball </td><td>11 times Earth </td></tr>  
<tr><td>Pluto </td><td>= grain of sand </td><td>1/5 of Earth </td></tr>
</table></center>
</li>
<li>Relative distances:
<br/>If the Sun was at one end of tennis court,  Earth would be at the other end
<br/>		Jupiter would be two football fields away,
<br/>		Pluto would be a mile away.
</li>	
<li>The astronomical unit (AU), the distance from the Earth to the Sun, is approximately 1.49598 x 10<sup>8</sup> km. </li>
<li>The mass of the Sun (one solar mass) is approximately 1.989 x 10<sup>30</sup> kg. </li>
<li>The mass of the Earth (one Earth mass) is approximately 5.9742 x 10<sup>24</sup> kg. </li>
</ul>

